    <title>Extremely Low Mass White Dwarf Pulsators</title>
    <abstract>ZZ Ceti stars are pulsating white dwarfs (WDs) with hydrogen-dominated atmospheres and are observed in a narrow temperature range, about 1500K wide. The actual position of the instability strip depends on the mass; the higher the mass, the hotter the stars start to pulsate. However, there are a couple variables with temperature and mass determined from low S/N spectra that would be outside the instability strip. When we compared their Galex colors with models, we found out that these objects are much less massive than previously thought. In fact, these stars are most likely to be the blue edge of the extremely low mass WDs (Hermes et al. 2012, 2013). The goal of this proposal is to obtain S/N~100 spectra to determine the atmospheric parameters of these two stars, in order to confirm their low mass nature or if additional parameters are placing the stars outside the strip. Extremely low mass WDs are themselves important objects, as they are the resulting products of binary evolution. </abstract>
